The paper discusses the use of game theory and reinforcement learning to model common-pool resource appropriation, which falls under the category of multi-agent systems. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.GT (Game Theory and Mechanism Design). The paper also uses deep reinforcement learning, which falls under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper discusses the emergent behavior of groups of agents, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the importance of exclusion, sustainability, and inequality, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI). Finally, the paper specifically mentions the use of a partially observed Markov game, which falls under the category of multi-agent reinforcement learning (cs.MA).
